\nRun these as separate passes. Preserve behavior unless a specific bug is found.\n\n### 1. Deletion Pass\n\nLook for speculative generality:\n\n- one-use traits\n- one-use structs\n- generic helpers with only one real caller\n- parameters added for imagined future agents\n- fields that are always `None` or always the same value\n- comments that repeat the code\n\nDelete or inline when the call s\n[TRUNCATED]\n `but` needs.\n- Prefer `pub(crate)` over `pub` when cross-module access is needed.\n- Keep typed errors at the library boundary.\n- Use `anyhow` only in app/CLI glue.\n- Prefer `&str` and `&Path` parameters when ownership is not needed.\n- Avoid clones inside loops unless ownership is genuinely required.\n- Derive `Debug` where it helps tests and diagnostics.\n\n### 5. Test Intent Pass\n\nTests should answer: \"What behavior would break if a maintainer changed this?\"\n\nHigh-value tests for this crate:\n\n- malformed final JSONL line is skipped\n- malformed middle JSONL line fails\n- empty lines do not affect record indexes\n- cwd mismatch fails\n- dry-run performs no GitMeta writes\n- repeated capture is idempotent\n- transcript append dedupe survives missing hash set state\n- Codex and Claude field extraction preserve the shared envelope shape\n- redaction catches plausible secrets without schema-specific allowlists\n\nAvoid tests that only restate local implementation structure.\n\n### 6. AI-Specific Review Pass\n\nAsk reviewers or subagents narrow questions:\n\n- What looks over-generalized for a two-agent POC?\n- What would a maintainer misunderstand six months from now?\n- Which name hides a concrete domain concept?\n- Which test would still pass if the behavior were subtly wrong?\n- Which dependency, helper, or module exists only because generated code tends\n  to over-structure things?\n\nDo not ask for a broad rewrite. The output should be small findings, not a new\narchitecture.\n\n## Cursor Note\n\nDo not force Cursor into the current JSONL parser